We introduce the notion of an `m`-admissible list of natural number: a list `[iâ‚€,â€¦,iâ‚™]` is said to be `m`-admissible if `iâ‚– â‰¤ m + k` for all valid index `k`. These lists are intended to uniquely represents either `P_Ïƒ` or `P_Î´` morphisms in `SimplexCategoryGenRel`.
We prove basic stability of such lists under some lists operation such as the tail.
We also introduce the notion of simplicial insertion, which is intended to be the algorithm on such normal forms representing composition on the right (for `P_Ïƒ` morphisms) or on the left (for `P_Î´` morphisms) by a single morphism, and we prove that this preserves admissibility.

Part of a series of PR formalising that `SimplexCategoryGenRel` is equivalent to `SimplexCategory`.

```suggestion
def IsAdmissible (L : List â„•) : Prop :=
```
Some definitions/lemmas may be put in the `IsAdmissible` namespace in order to allow dot notation.

```suggestion
def IsAdmissible.getElemAsFin {L : List â„•} (hl : IsAdmissible m L) (k : â„•)
    (hk : k < L.length) : Fin (m + k + 1) :=
```
(Untested, but in principale, we could use this definition as `hl.getElemAsFin k hk`.)

Untested, but `h` seems unnecessary.
```suggestion
  âˆ€ (k : â„•), k < L.length â†’ L[k] â‰¤ m + k
```
Without a parameter, `L[k]` is unhappy. `(_ : k < L.length)` works but if we have to put it we might as well name it.

These `obtain` (here and below) are unnecessary as you should be have to do `hl.1` or `hl.2`. (If you prefer, you may alternatively introduce lemmas `IsAdmissible.sorted` and `IsAdmissible.le`, so that you could do `hl.sorted` or `hl.le`, which may increase the readibility of the code.)
